Project Statement
Course: Fundamentals of AI and ML
Submission Type: BYOP — Bring Your Own Project
Project Title: Suspicious Transaction Detection

Problem Being Solved
Digital payments have become a part of daily life. UPI, card payments, net banking transfers — people use them without thinking twice. And for the most part, that trust is fine. But fraud happens, and when it does, it usually doesn't look dramatic. It looks like a few small transactions at odd hours, or a purchase from a merchant the user has never interacted with, or a sudden burst of activity in the middle of the night.
The systems banks currently use to catch this are mostly rule-based. If a transaction crosses a fixed amount, flag it. If it comes from outside a certain region, block it. These rules catch the obvious stuff but miss everything that falls just below the threshold or comes packaged to look normal. A smarter approach would look at the full picture of a transaction and ask whether the combination of signals adds up to something suspicious.
That is what this project tries to do.

Why I Chose This Problem
This did not start as a random topic pick. A family member had their debit card compromised, and because each individual transaction was small, the bank did not catch it for nearly three days. By the time anything was flagged, a significant amount had already been lost. That incident stayed with me. It felt like a problem that technology should be able to solve better than it currently does, and this course gave me the right tools to take a real shot at it.

What the Project Does
The project builds a full fraud detection pipeline from scratch in Python. Here is what it covers:

Creates a realistic synthetic transaction dataset with both normal and fraudulent entries mixed in
Builds meaningful features from raw transaction data like time of day, how far the transaction is from home, how many transactions happened that day, and the risk level of the merchant
Trains a Random Forest Classifier that learns from labeled examples of normal and fraudulent transactions
Trains an Isolation Forest that detects unusual transactions without needing any labels at all
Evaluates both models using precision, recall, F1 score, and ROC-AUC rather than just accuracy, because accuracy alone is misleading when fraud cases are rare
Generates visualizations including a confusion matrix, feature importance chart, and transaction amount distribution
Includes a working function that takes a single new transaction and tells you whether it looks suspicious


