Dataset Used
Since real transaction data is sensitive and not publicly available with proper fraud labels, the dataset was generated synthetically. It contains 5,000 transactions designed to behave the way real data does, with normal transactions clustering around daytime hours and modest amounts, and fraudulent ones more likely to appear at night, at high-risk merchants, and in sudden bursts. The fraud rate was kept at 5 percent, which is close to real-world figures and makes the classification problem genuinely difficult.
No real customer data was used at any point.

Models and Tools

Language: Python 3.8+
Libraries: scikit-learn, pandas, numpy, matplotlib, seaborn
Models: RandomForestClassifier and IsolationForest from scikit-learn
Evaluation: classification_report, confusion_matrix, roc_auc_score


Key Results
The Random Forest model ended up with a ROC-AUC score of around 0.96 on the test set. It caught roughly 88 out of every 100 fraudulent transactions correctly, with a precision of about 0.82, which means false alarms were kept at a level a human reviewer could actually manage. The features that carried the most weight were merchant risk score, transaction amount, distance from home, and daily transaction count. That lines up with what you would intuitively expect a fraud analyst to look at too.

